 the wide range of indigenous individuals who used knowledge to subvert, undermine, critique, and sometimes enhance colonial power. Seeking to understand the political, social, and cultural impact of indigenous intellectuals, the contributors examine both ideological and practical forms of knowledge. Their understanding of "intellectual" encompasses the creators of written texts and visual representations, functionaries and bureaucrats who interacted with colonial agents and institutions, and organic intellectuals.Contributors. Elizabeth Hill Boone, Kathryn Burns, John Charles, Alan Durston, María Elena Martínez, Tristan Platt, Gabriela Ramos, Susan Schroeder, John F. Schwaller, Camilla Townsend, Eleanor Wake, Yanna Yannakakis   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aIndians of MexicoxCivilization. 0aIndians of MexicoxIntellectual life. 0aIndigenous peopleszAndesxCivilization. 0aIndigenous peopleszAndesxIntellectual life. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh1 aTownsend, Camilla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWake, Eleanor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoone, Elizabeth Hill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRamos, Gabriela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchwaller, John Frederick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharles, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurns, Kathryn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartínez, María Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRamos, Gabriela, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchroeder, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb